{{Infobox philosopher |region = |era = |color = lightsteelblue |image = |image_size = |caption = |name = Peggy DesAutels |birth_date = |birth_place = |death_date = |school_tradition = |main_interests = [[moral psychology]], [[feminist philosophy]] and [[philosophy of mind]] |notable_ideas = |institutions = [[University of Dayton]], [[Washington University of St. Louis]] |influences = |influenced = |signature = }} '''Peggy DesAutels''' is Professor of Philosophy at the [[University of Dayton]].<ref name=obio>{{cite web|title=Peggy DesAutels|url=http://academic.udayton.edu/PeggyDesAutels/|accessdate=29 July 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070307005634/http://academic.udayton.edu/PeggyDesAutels/|archivedate=7 March 2007|df=}}</ref> She works in [[moral psychology]], [[feminist philosophy]] and [[philosophy of mind]] and [[cognitive science]].<ref name=ubio>{{cite web|last=DesAutels|first=Peggy|title=Peggy DesAutels|url=http://www.peggydesautels.com/|accessdate=29 July 2013}}</ref>
== Education == DesAutels received her Ph.D. in Philosophy from [[Washington University of St. Louis]] in 1995 after earning an M.S. in computer science and an M.A. in philosophy.<ref name=obio/><ref name=ubio/>
== Career == From 2010-2013, DesAutels served as the chair of the Committee on the Status of Women of the American Philosophical Association; she currently serves as an ex officio member of the committee as the Director of the Site Visit Program.<ref name=ubio/><ref name=apacsw>{{cite web|title=Committee Members - APA Committee on the Status of Women|url=http://www.apaonlinecsw.org/members|publisher=American Philosophical Association}}</ref><ref name=ihe>{{cite news|last=Strausheim|first=Carl|title=Handling the Harassers|url=http://www.insidehighered.com/news/2013/03/29/apa-forms-committee-tackle-sexual-harassment-philosophy-departments|accessdate=29 July 2013|newspaper=Inside Higher Ed|date=29 March 2013}}</ref>
As chair of the Committee on the Status of Women of the American Philosophical Association, DesAutels was outspoken against the problems facing women philosophers, criticizing the lack of gender parity in philosophy, as well as the prevalence of sexual harassment in academia, the underrepresentation of women philosophers in tenure-track positions, and the number of philosophy conferences with all-male lineups.<ref name=ihe/><ref name=shun>{{cite news|last=Jaschik|first=Scott|title=A call to Shun|url=http://www.insidehighered.com/news/2011/03/30/philosophers_consider_what_to_do_about_sexual_harassment|accessdate=29 July 2013|newspaper=Inside Higher Ed|date=30 March 2011}}</ref> DesAutels was named Distinguished Woman in Philosophy for 2014 by the Eastern Division of [[Society for Women in Philosophy]].
DesAutels was also a research leader on a $3 million National Science Foundation (NSF) ADVANCE grant, awarded to a consortium including University of Dayton, aimed at advancing the recruitment and advancement of women in STEM (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) fields.<ref name=wright>{{cite news|last=Gottschlich|first=Stephanie|title=Improving the climate for women in STEM fields: LEADER consortium kicks off Monday|url=http://www.wright.edu/cgibin/news_item.cgi?1503|accessdate=29 July 2013|newspaper=Wright|date=7 November 2008}}</ref>
== Publications == DesAutels is the editor of several volumes in feminist ethics and moral psychology.
