'''Pre-theoretical belief''' has been an important notion in some areas of [[linguistics]] and [[philosophy]], especially [[Phenomenology (philosophy)|phenomenology]] and older versions of “ordinary language” philosophy. It is often assumed, rightly or wrongly, that language depends on mental concepts, and that certain concepts are [[innate]]. These innate concepts provide sources of very basic linguistic competency, available to any natural language speaker that enables more complex forms of language use, including philosophical, scientific, or other types of technical language. These basic concepts, in combination, may form basic propositional attitudes about things and events. Often “pre-theoretical belief” refers to these basic propositional attitudes. Also, “pre-theoretical beliefs” may refer to simple intuitions.

''Pre-theoretic belief'' is a term used in philosophical arguments for and against [[libertarianism]] and [[determinism]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Balaguer|first1=Mark|title=Free will as an open scientific problem excerpt: Why There Are No Good Arguments for or against Determinism (or Any Other Thesis That Would Establish or Refute Libertarianism) ...|date=2010|publisher=MIT Press|isbn=9780262319775|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6F_FAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT15&lpg=PT15&dq=Pre-theoretic+belief&source=bl&ots=0H5HcHCt6L&sig=IBnSZJtjrLBWskIV63cHEJqqPr0&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjYt67tpuTXAhUKMd8KHaZVBK4Q6AEIRjAF#v=onepage&q=Pre-theoretic%20belief&f=false|accessdate=29 November 2017}}</ref>

