{{Infobox economist | name = William Landes | school_tradition = [[Chicago School of Economics]]
| image = Landes_william_thumb.jpg | image_size = | caption = | birth_date = c. {{Birth year and age|1939}} | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | nationality = [[United States]] | institution = [[University of Chicago Law School]] | field = [[Law and economics]] | alma_mater = [[Columbia University]] | influences = | influenced = | contributions = | awards = | signature = <!-- file name only --> | repec_prefix = f | repec_id = pla327 }}
'''William M. Landes''' (born c. 1939) is an American [[economist]] who has written about the [[Law and economics|economic analysis of law]]. He is a fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences, which cited him for his work in the field. Landes also is the original founder (with [[Richard Posner]] and Andrew Rosenfield) of Lexecon, a consulting firm.
Landes received his [[Ph.D.]] in Economics from [[Columbia University]]. He taught in the Economics Departments of [[Stanford University]], Columbia University, the Graduate Center of the [[City University of New York]] and The [[University of Chicago]] before joining the faculty of the [[University of Chicago Law School]], where he is emeritus.
Landes is also a board member of the Smart Museum of Art, which is located in the University of Chicago's Hyde Park Campus. The Elisabeth & William M. Landes Gallery within the Smart Museum of Art features works created between the 1880s and the late 1950s.
Landes is a collector of left-wing and homoerotic art.<ref>[http://visitshoremagazine.com/articles/2006/11/18/shorelines/culture_nut/doc4553ab569c6dd652675889.txt Conservative Among Left-Wing Artists]</ref>
==Selected bibliography== * ''The Economic Structure of Intellectual Property Law'' (Harvard Univ. Press 2003) (with [[Richard A. Posner]]). * "The Economics of Legal Disputes Over The Ownership of Works of Art and Other Collectibles, " in Essays in the Economics of the Arts, V. A. Ginsburgh & P.-M. Menger, eds. (Elsevier Science, 1996) (with [[Richard A. Posner]]). * ''The Economic Structure of Tort Law'', ([[Harvard Univ. Press]] 1987) (with [[Richard A. Posner]]). * "Causation in Tort Law: An Economic Approach," [[Journal of Legal Studies]] (January 1983) (with [[Richard A. Posner]]). * "An Economic Theory of Intentional Torts,"[[International Review of Law and Economics]] (December 1981) (with [[Richard A. Posner]]). * "The Positive Economic Theory of Tort Law," [[Georgia Law Review]] (Summer 1981) (with [[Richard A. Posner]]). * ''Essays in the Economics of Crime and Punishment'', ([[National Bureau of Economic Research]] 1974)(edited with [[Gary S. Becker]]).
